<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="naming-and-domains">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Systematic methodology for generating product names and validating domain/handle availability across .com, .io, GitHub, npm, PyPI, and social handles.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>naming</tag>
      <tag>branding</tag>
      <tag>domain</tag>
      <tag>pre-launch</tag>
      <tag>solopreneur</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-24</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Naming and Domains</title>
    <summary>Systematic methodology for generating product names and validating domain/handle availability before launch. Combines 7 naming strategies (descriptive, invented, compound, metaphor, portmanteau, alliteration, acronym) with parallel availability checking across .com/.io/.co, GitHub, npm, PyPI, and social handles. Generate 30+ candidates, filter by availability and criteria, then shortlist 3 viable options.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Pre-launch naming is a single high-stakes decision with permanent consequences: an unavailable .com, a trademark conflict, or a culturally negative meaning can kill a brand before launch. Systematic multi-strategy generation with availability gating prevents the "name everything looks great until we check" failure mode. LLMs default to mode-collapsed names (Spark, Nova, Atlas, Loop); explicit anti-pattern injection forces diversity.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch: locking name + domain + core social handles in one batch.</item>
        <item>Rebrand or sub-product launch: testing 20+ candidates against availability and trademark.</item>
        <item>Naming a project where domain availability is the binding constraint (no .com → no go).</item>
        <item>Generating localized variants (UA/EN/DE) of a brand for multi-region launch.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Established brand — naming agents will not improve mature trademarks.</item>
        <item>Highly regulated industries (pharma, finance) where naming triggers regulator review — manual lawyer step required.</item>
        <item>Internal/code-name only — domain check is wasted effort.</item>
        <item>No budget for trademark attorney — agent-generated trademark pre-filter is informational risk band, not legal clearance.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="naming-strategies">
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply all 7 strategies to keywords and generate at least 20 candidates before evaluating any.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-strategy generation produces names that cluster; diversity requires parallel exploration across strategy types.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Descriptive — states what the product does (Dropbox, YouTube)</item>
        <item>Invented — made-up word with no prior meaning (Spotify, Kodak)</item>
        <item>Compound — two meaningful words combined (Facebook, Snapchat)</item>
        <item>Metaphor — symbolic meaning borrowed from another domain (Amazon, Apple)</item>
        <item>Portmanteau — syllables from two words blended (Pinterest = pin + interest, Instagram = instant + telegram)</item>
        <item>Alliteration — repeated initial sound aids memory (PayPal, Coca-Cola)</item>
        <item>Acronym — initialism for the product's full name (IBM, NASA)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="good-name-criteria">
      <rule>
        <statement>Reject any candidate that fails more than one of these six tests: easy to spell, easy to pronounce, memorable, .com domain available, no trademark conflicts, works internationally.</statement>
        <rationale>A name that fails on domain or trademark is unusable regardless of how memorable it is; a name with pronunciation ambiguity fails at word-of-mouth.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Target 5-10 characters. Avoid hyphens, numbers, and ambiguous letters (l/I/1, O/0).</statement>
        <rationale>Short names attract premium pricing; very long names are unmemorable; ambiguous characters kill voice spelling.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="generation-process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define brand attributes (3-5 adjectives) and keyword buckets (product, benefit, emotion) before generating any names.</statement>
        <rationale>Names generated without a brief converge on generic register. Brief anchors diversity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Step 1: Define brand attributes (3-5 adjectives)</item>
        <item>Step 2: List keywords by bucket — product, benefit, emotion</item>
        <item>Step 3: Apply each strategy to each keyword bucket</item>
        <item>Step 4: Generate 20+ candidates</item>
        <item>Step 5: Filter by availability (domain + trademark)</item>
        <item>Step 6: Test pronunciation with 5 people from target market</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="llm-anti-patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Prompting an LLM without explicit forbidden-words list produces names ending in -ly, -ify, -hub, or starting with Smart-, AI-.</description>
        <reason>LLMs are mode-collapsed on startup naming patterns. Same prompt yields Lify, Spark, Loop, Flux, Atlas, Nova, Pulse repeatedly. Diversity requires an anti-pattern list in the prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting a name without native-speaker pronunciation test.</description>
        <reason>Agent-generated names like "Krapp", "Pschitt", or "Sega" (Italian: saw/handjob) have culturally negative meanings agents miss. Requires L1 speaker review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <example type="good" title="Task Management Tool — complete generation run">
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Attributes: Simple, fast, powerful
Keywords: tasks, workflow, automation
Anti-patterns: NO [-ly, -ify, -hub, AI-, smart-, Spark, Atlas, Nova]

Generated: TaskFlow (compound), Tasko (invented), QuickTask (descriptive), Flowdo (portmanteau), Taskr (invented)
Filtered: TaskFlow (.com available, 8 chars, 2 syllables)
Winner: TaskFlow
]]></code>
    </example>
    <section name="check-priority">
      <rule>
        <statement>Check .com first. If .com is taken by an active product, move to the next name candidate rather than accepting an alternative TLD for a serious brand.</statement>
        <rationale>.com is still the default for credibility in B2B. .io is acceptable for devtools. .ai only if ML product and budget tolerates premium. Skip .xyz/.tech for serious brands.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Priority 1 — .com domain (essential for credibility)</item>
        <item>Priority 2 — GitHub org (essential for open-source)</item>
        <item>Priority 3 — .io domain (acceptable for tech products)</item>
        <item>Priority 4 — Twitter/X handle (important for marketing)</item>
        <item>Priority 5 — .co domain (alternative TLD)</item>
        <item>Priority 6 — LinkedIn company URL slug (nice to have)</item>
        <item>Also check: npm package, PyPI package if applicable</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="availability-actions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Register handles on all platforms in the same hour as registering the domain — even if unused — to prevent squatting.</statement>
        <rationale>GitHub org, npm/PyPI, Twitter, LinkedIn — squatters monitor new domain registrations and claim matching handles within hours.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Available → Register immediately</item>
        <item>Premium (priced) → Consider if under $5K for revenue-generating product</item>
        <item>Taken (parked greater than 5 years, price greater than $5K) → Walk away for non-revenue projects</item>
        <item>Taken (active product) → Move to next name candidate</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="alternative-domain-strategies">
      <p>When primary .com is taken, try in order before accepting an alternative TLD:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Add "get" prefix: gettaskflow.com</item>
        <item>Add "app" or "hq" suffix: taskflowhq.com</item>
        <item>Different TLD: taskflow.io</item>
        <item>Creative spelling (only if still unambiguous): taskflw.com</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="trademark-check">
      <rule>
        <statement>Trademark check must end at a human attorney. Agent USPTO TESS output is an informational risk band, not legal clearance.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents miss similar marks (phonetic, design). A free .com that infringes is worse than a paid premium that is clear.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating agent trademark pre-filter as legal clearance.</description>
        <reason>USPTO TESS HTML changes yearly, scrapes break, and phonetic similarity is not caught by string matching. Agent output is risk-band only.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>WHOIS responses vary by registry — "no match" / "not found" / "no entries" / "AVAILABLE" are all different strings; agent regex misses some.</description>
        <reason>Some TLDs deny WHOIS to non-authenticated clients (.de needs DENIC TCP); agents falsely report "available". Always confirm at registrar API, not just WHOIS.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Price scraping stale domains without re-fetching within 48h of registration decision.</description>
        <reason>Premium domain pricing fluctuates; scraped prices can be weeks old and the listed price may have changed or the domain may have been claimed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <example type="good" title="TaskFlow availability: primary taken, fallback found">
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
taskflow.com     → Taken (active SaaS product)
gettaskflow.com  → Available → Register
taskflow.io      → Available → Register as backup
@taskflow        → Taken
@gettaskflow     → Available → Register

Recommendation: gettaskflow.com + @gettaskflow
]]></code>
    </example>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>.com is still king for B2B; .io for devtools; .ai for ML products only if budget tolerates premium. Skip .xyz/.tech for serious brands.</item>
        <item>Trademark greater than availability: a free .com that infringes is worse than a paid premium that's clear.</item>
        <item>5-10 character sweet spot: short → premium-priced; long → unmemorable.</item>
        <item>Pronunciation test live: get 5 humans to say the name from text alone. If 2+ stumble, drop it.</item>
        <item>Negative-space check: Google "[name] meaning" + native speakers in target markets — agents miss culturally negative associations.</item>
        <item>Reserve handles before announcing: GitHub org, npm/PyPI, Twitter, LinkedIn — even if unused, reserve in same hour as registering domain.</item>
        <item>Don't chase parked premiums: if a domain has been parked greater than 5 years and asking price is greater than $5k for a non-revenue project, walk away.</item>
        <item>Avoid hyphens, numbers, and ambiguous letters (l/I/1, O/0) — kill memorability, hurt voice spelling.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/naming-brief.md" purpose="Structured brief capturing brand attributes, keywords, candidates table, and top 3 recommendations."/>
      <template path="templates/domain-check-report.md" purpose="Domain/handle availability matrix with trademark check section and fallback alternatives."/>
      <template path="templates/check-names.sh" purpose="Bash script: reads names.txt, runs WHOIS + GitHub + npm + PyPI + Twitter checks, outputs matrix.csv."/>
    </templates>
    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/check-names.sh" purpose="Bulk availability runner: WHOIS + handle checks in parallel, outputs CSV matrix."/>
    </scripts>
